story: MIT African Students' Association - ASA added an event.
message:
"Sometimes the place you are used to is no the place you belong. You belong where you believe you belong. Where is that place for you?" Robert, Queen of Katwe.

Come and enjoy PLANTAINS, CHICKEN, AND DRINKS (And a WARM company of cause) whilst watching the award winning movie.

Based on the true story.

A lovely inspiring story with an amazing cast. This is one of those uplifting intelligent movies that you really can’t fault too much, and it’s a welcome break from all the blockbusters movies. It is cliched but even that is handled well as it offers some powerful lessons about life, perseverance, and success against all odds

story: MIT African Students' Association - ASA added 2 new photos — with Kudzaishe George Zharare and 5 others.
message:
"KOLA NUTS WITH THE ELDERS":

MIT-African students in a great dinner yesterday with the MIT Faculty and Staff whose life work and studies are highly aligned with the African continent.

The staff includes:
- Julia Reynolds-Cuéllar, the managing director of the MIT-AFRICA Initiative, which is the first organized public face for MIT engagement in Africa that communicates and coordinates engagement in Africa, as well as acts as a point of entry for new partnerships, while enhancing collaboration among faculty, and 
-Lauren Siegel, the Program Coordinator to MIT-AFRICA Initiative

The faculty includes:
- Amah Edoh, an anthropologist whose research interests are at the intersection of material culture, creative production, and African studies.
- Evan Lieberman, the Total Professor of Political Science and Contemporary Africa who conducts research in the field of comparative politics, with a focus on development and ethnic conflict in sub-Saharan Africa
- Jacob K. Olupona, Professor of African Religious Traditions, with a joint appointment as Professor of African and African American Studies in the Faculty of Arts and Sciences
- Tavneet Suri, an Associate Professor of Applied Economics at the MIT Sloan School of Management whose expertise is as a development economist, specialized in Sub-Saharan Africa.

Your support will go a long way in sharing an inspiring story of the journey of four of our alums

https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/arthurmusah/one-day-i-too-go-fly-documentary-post-production

story: MIT African Students' Association - ASA added an event.
message: Meet the members of the African Students Association, Black Students Union and Caribbean Club for our BoY BBQ. You don't want to miss the chill vibes, good music and of course delicious food! This is a good time to have fun, say hi to old friends, and give freshmen a word of advice. Hope to see y'all there.

"Even though our opinions on what country makes the best jollof rice sharply differ, we can all agree that chatting over jollof rice is a great way to engage the community." 
'We won the Harvard game (of course) but unfortunately lost to BU"
Check out more about what we've been up to by following the link:
http://africans.mit.edu/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/summer_2017.pdf

Did you for a moment doubt the puissance of the Africa Rising rhetoric? There can be no better evidence to this new paradigm than seeing young Africans taking on the baton.
Today, we congratulate our alum, former ASA Vice President and pioneer of the Africa Learning Circle, Hassan Kane, on his appointment on the advisory board of the African Development University-ADU, a Pan-African university in Niger with the aim of training the next generation of African game-changers. Read more on his page:
https://www.facebook.com/hassan.kane.7/posts/10213325279903998

This last week has been a tragic time for Sierra Leone. Immense mudslides and floods have already killed more than 450 Sierra Leonean citizens, and more than 150 of them were children. More than 600 others have already gone missing, and more than 20 000 have already been displaced by the mudslides, including 5000 children. 

The MIT African students Association stands with Sierra Leone in these tragic events. Our prayers and thoughts are with everyone who was affected.  

Checkout our blog to learn more about what you can do to help. 
http://africans.mit.edu/we-stand-with-sierra-leone/

story: MIT African Students' Association - ASA added an event.
message:
Sisonke is a Xhosa/Zulu/Ndebele word for togetherness.
 It means “you don’t need to share DNA with a person for them to be your family”.

Come, join us in celebrating TOGETHERNESS in the diverse, yet unified and rich African culture. 

Explore the different foods, music, fashion and dances that Africa has to offer. You won't be dissapointed.

Show: 6:00pm - 9:00pm
After party: 9:30pm - 1:00am

Be there or be squared!!

message:
MIT African Students Association is deeply honored to announce that our keynote speaker for the  2017 Cultural Night is none other than Professor Calestous Juma. 
--
Professor Calestous Juma is an internationally recognized authority in the application of science and technology to sustainable development worldwide. He was named one of the 100 most influential Africans in 2012, 2013 and 2014 by the New African magazine. He is Professor of the Practice of International Development and Faculty Chair of the Innovation for Economic Development Executive Program at the Harvard Kennedy School. In addition, Professor Juma is Director of the School's Science, Technology and Globalization Project as well as the Agricultural Innovation in Africa Project funded by the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation. He has made significant contributions to understanding the dynamic role of technological innovation in economic transformation in developing countries. Read more about Professor Juma's stellar accomplishments here: https://www.hks.harvard.edu/faculty/calestous-juma
--
The title of his speech will be "INNOVATION AND AFRICAN REGIONAL INTEGRATION".
As you can see, Professor Juma is not the kind of person we get to hear from everyday. Another reason why you want to secure your spot at the night of celebrating African culture and togetherness.
GET YOUR TICKET HERE:
https://mit.universitytickets.com/w/event.aspx?id=721&cid=35&p=1

- Chinua Achebe
